universe fixture <strong>Sally Buzbee</strong>, my buddies from BPI, etcete=
ra. It was a rare night in Washington, refreshingly devoid of cynicism and =
filled with the promise of citizenship. Everyone in that room, more or less=
, had vociferously criticized the president on their air or in their copy=
=E2=80=94for being selfish, for holding on too long, for pardoning <strong>=
Hunter</strong>, for effectively handing the people=E2=80=99s house back to=
 Trump=E2=80=94and yet, they all wanted to gather to shake his hand a final
time and wish him well on his journey back to private life. Meanwhile, the =
senescent president could have easily declined the event this year on accou=
nt of his travels, the exigencies of winding down his administration, or so=
me other passable white lie. (Trust me, social Washington was already aflut=
ter with commentary about the fact that the Bidens were throwing fewer holi=
day parties this season=E2=80=A6) Instead, he manned the rope line, greetin=
g hundreds of well-wishers with a firm, if frail,
handshake.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">As I prepared to disembark to the real=
